{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631382"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:27:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:27:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17371"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17371"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10061"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70366"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10061"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17371"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55830"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"11206"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23554"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23626"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70366"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGender bias in healthcare remains a significant issue that can affect patient outcomes. Historical medical research has often focused predominantly on male subjects, leading to gaps in understanding of disease presentations and treatment responses in women.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a documented effect of gender bias in healthcare?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Women are more likely to receive diagnostic testing for heart disease","Women with heart attacks are more likely to be misdiagnosed","Pain symptoms are taken more seriously in female patients","Treatment delays for acute coronary syndrome are shorter in women","Female-specific symptoms are well-represented in clinical guidelines"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EResearch has shown that \u003Cstrong\u003Ewomen with heart attacks are more likely to be misdiagnosed\u003C/strong\u003E compared to men, often because their symptoms may differ from the \u0027classic\u0027 male presentation that has historically dominated medical education and research.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWomen are more likely to receive diagnostic testing for heart disease\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as women consistently receive fewer cardiac investigations than men.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPain symptoms are taken more seriously in female patients\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as women\u0027s pain complaints are frequently undertreated or dismissed by healthcare providers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETreatment delays for acute coronary syndrome are shorter in women\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as women typically experience longer delays in receiving treatment for cardiac events.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFemale-specific symptoms are well-represented in clinical guidelines\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as most clinical guidelines remain based on male-pattern disease presentations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis gender bias in healthcare can lead to delayed diagnosis, inappropriate treatment, and worse outcomes for women with cardiovascular disease. Recognition of these disparities has led to efforts to better understand and address sex-specific differences in disease presentation and treatment response.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gender bias in healthcare leads to systematic differences in how medical conditions are diagnosed and treated between men and women.","Implicit gender bias can affect clinical decision-making and contribute to health disparities.","Recognition of gender bias in medical research has led to requirements for inclusion of women in clinical trials."],"references":["Stephenson AL, Diehl AB, Dzubinski LM, McErlean M, Huppertz J, Sidhu M. An Exploration of Gender Bias Affecting Women in Medicine. Adv Health Care Manag. 2021;20:10.1108/S1474-823120210000020004. doi:10.1108/S1474-823120210000020004"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55830"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17371"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55830"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T19:55:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T19:56:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10061"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70366"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/t